'''Mark Hamill''' (born on [[September 25]], [[1950s#1951|1951]]) is an [[Wikipedia:Actor|actor]], best known for his portrayal of [[Luke Skywalker]] in the original and sequel ''[[Star Wars]]'' trilogies.

==Biography==
===Original Trilogy===
{{Quote|I lit up when I found out that they were going to make my face a mask on a box of cereal. With little dots where to cut my eyes out. The idea of me being on bubble gum cards... I thought you had to have athletic ability to be a bubble gum card. So I enjoyed the merchandising aspect of it.|Mark Hamill, on the success of ''Star Wars''|<ref name="Empire of Dreams">''[[Empire of Dreams: The Story of the Star Wars Trilogy]]''</ref>}}
[[File:HamillGuinness-MOSW.png|thumb|left|250px|Hamill enjoys a lighthearted moment with [[Alec Guinness]] on the set of ''Star Wars''.]]
Hamill found fame with the hero role of [[Luke Skywalker]] in [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'']] in [[1977]]. He was originally cast as David on "''Eight Is Enough''," and asked to be released from his contract before ''Star Wars'' came out because he sensed the movie would be successful. Hamill wanted to focus on his movie career. At last his producers agreed to remove him from the series.

In [[January 11]], 1977, a day before he was set to shoot one of the final scenes needed for the film, Hamill was involved in a car accident that caused minor damage to his face. A double was used for the scene of Luke racing across the desert in his landspeeder while Mark was hospitalized. In an A&E Network Biography special, "Mark Hamill: A Force to Be Reckoned With," the auto accident and its consequences are recounted by Mark's family.

[[File:MarkHamillSnowspeeder-TESB-BTS.png|thumb|right|300px|Mark Hamill behind the scenes on ''The Empire Strikes Back'']]
As a result of this scarring, Hamill wore an extensive amount of facial makeup when he reprised his role as Luke for ''[[The Star Wars Holiday Special]]'', which was released in [[1978]]. A common myth is that the slight damage to Mark's face was explained in-universe in [[Star Wars: Episode V The Empire Strikes Back|''The Empire Strikes Back'']] by the scene where he is mauled by a [[Wampa]]. His son [[Nathan Hamill|Nathan]] was born while he was shooting Episode V. Before the film's climactic lightsaber duel between Luke Skywalker and [[Anakin Skywalker|Darth Vader]], Lucas told Hamill the truth about Vader being Luke's father.

===Sequel Trilogy===
{{Quote|All of this, happening to me again was... it's hard to put into words. I figured when the prequels came out, plus a few years, people would forget about us. But it never really went away.|Mark Hamill on the sequel trilogy|<ref name="Luke comes home">{{WebCite|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/11/19/star-wars-last-jedi-luke-millennium-falcon|text=Luke comes home: Mark Hamill's heartbreaking return to the Millennium Falcon in ''The Last Jedi''|author=Anthony Breznican|date=2017-11-19|work=''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''|archivedate=20171120003143}}</ref>}}
[[File:MarkHamillStar-SWYBYNE.png|thumb|left|300px|Hamill poses for a picture when presented his star on the Walk of Fame in Hollywood in 2018]]
[[George Lucas]] once considered doing a [[sequel trilogy]] in which Hamill would reprise the role of an older and wiser Luke Skywalker as an [[Obi-Wan Kenobi|Obi-Wan]]-like [[Jedi Master]] in his sixties training a new era of [[Jedi Knight]]s, including the protagonist of the sequels set against the backdrop of the rebuilding of the [[New Republic|Republic]] and the dismantlement of the last remnants of the [[Galactic Empire|Empire]]. It would be filmed around 2011. Lucas long dismissed this as an off-hand comment, but then on [[October 30]], [[2012]], the talk of a possible sequel, to be released in [[2015]], was back in the news when [[Lucasfilm]] was sold to [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]]. After production officially started on [[Star Wars: Episode VII The Force Awakens|''The Force Awakens'']], rumors spread that Disney would hire Hamill and the other stars of the [[original trilogy]] to reprise their roles. The rumors were eventually confirmed in [[2014]] with the first major casting announcement, which confirmed that Mark Hamill would play Luke Skywalker once again. Hamill received a star on the Walk of Fame in Hollywood in [[2018]].

===''Star Wars'' voice cameos and advocacy===
In [[2021]], Hamill responded on [[Wikipedia:Twitter|Twitter]] to a tweet by the official [[Wookieepedia]] account about his voice cameo<ref name="Tweet: Re Wookieepedia">{{Twitter|HamillHimself|status/1417873951229767680|Mark Hamill|quote=Did you know... I voiced multiple secret voice-cameos in every movie released since 2015?<nowiki>* *</nowiki>(Sequels, Solo, Rogue One)|archivedate=20210721154755}}</ref> as [[EV-9D9]] in ''[[Star Wars: The Mandalorian]]'' episode "[[Chapter 5: The Gunslinger]]."<ref name="Disney Gallery">{{DisneyGallery|Connections}}</ref> Hamill said that he had provided voice cameos for every ''Star Wars'' film released since 2015.<ref name="Tweet: Re Wookieepedia" /> Although he had tweeted about this previously<ref name="Tweet: Hamill secret">{{Twitter|HamillHimself|status/1274433056405741568|Mark Hamill|quote=Now that @themandalorian secret is out-might as well reveal I am vocally represented in ALL SW films except the Prequels. Thanks to @matthewood for using me in Rogue One, Solo & the Sequels, so I DO have lines in . Hint: Look for parts played by Patrick Williams.|archivedate=20200620201451}}</ref> and shared his pseudonym, "William M. Patrick" for his older and younger brothers,<ref name="Tweet: Hamill pseudonym">
{{Twitter|HamillHimself|status/1275208409248174080|Mark Hamill|quote=It was never about billing (L- R-) or salary. It was for fun & the fans & because I❤️! I misremembered my pseudonym as "Patrick Williams"-It was actually "William M. Patrick" (for my older & younger brothers) I'm not telling what the M. stands for.|archivedate=20200622233445}}</ref> his response to Wookieepedia was picked up by media outlets such as [[Wikipedia:People (magazine)|People]]<ref name="People">{{WebCite|url=https://people.com/movies/mark-hamill-reveals-hes-secretly-appeared-in-every-star-wars-movie-since-2015|text="Mark Hamill Reveals He's Secretly Appeared in Every ''Star Wars'' Movie Since 2015"|author=Ale Russian|date=2021-07-23|work=[[Wikipedia:People (magazine)|''People'']]|archivedate=20210724034858}}</ref>
and [[Wikipedia:IGN|IGN]].<ref name="IGN">{{WebCite|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/mark-hamill-secret-voice-cameo-every-star-wars-movie-since-2015|text="Mark Hamill Did Secret Voice Cameos for Every Star Wars Movie Since 2015"|author=Wesley LeBlanc|date=2021-07-21|work=[[Wikipedia:IGN|''IGN'']]|archivedate=20210723023802}}</ref>

In September [[2022]], Hamill joined [[Wikipedia:Ukraine|Ukraine's]] [[Wikipedia:United24|United24]] crowdfunding campaign as an ambassador to acquire [[Wikipedia:Unmanned aerial vehicle|reconnaissance drones]], with [[Wikipedia:President of Ukraine|Ukrainian President]] [[Wikipedia:Volodymyr Zelenskyy|Volodymyr Zelenskyy]] thanking Hamill's support and echoing ''Star Wars''{{'}} theme that "good will triumph over evil and light will overcome darkness."<ref name="U24">{{WebCite|url=https://apnews.com/article/mark-hamill-ukraine-drones-46cfb2c53d43e7e1b4e270d0292a5f32|text=Mark Hamill talks fundraising for Ukraine, love of politics|author=Martina Rebecca Inchingolo|date=2022-12-14|work=[[Wikipedia:Associated Press|Associated Press]]|archivedate=20221214175707}}</ref> In March 2023, Hamill voiced the English-language version of Ukraine's "Air Alert" app.<ref name="Hamill air alert">{{WebCite|url=https://apnews.com/article/russia-ukraine-star-wars-luke-hamill-app-08ec03bf1a2c9c0378857090079f00f9|text=Mark Hamill lends 'Star Wars' voice to Ukrainian air-raid app|author=John Leicester|date=2023-03-28|work=[[Wikipedia:Associated Press|Associated Press]]|archiveurl=https://archive.is/t7jco}}</ref>

===References to ''Star Wars''===
Mark Hamill appeared as Luke Skywalker in a few shows, including [[Wikipedia:Bob Hope|''The Bob Hope All Star Christmas Comedy Special'']], ''[[The Muppet Show]]'', [[Wikipedia:Family Guy|''Family Guy'']], [[Wikipedia:Robot Chicken|''Robot Chicken'']], and [[Wikipedia:The Late Show With Stephen Colbert|''The Late Show With Stephen Colbert'']].<ref name="Colbert">{{WebCite|url=https://www.avclub.com/mark-hamill-indulges-stephen-colberts-inner-star-wars-g-1821145930|text=Mark Hamill indulges Stephen Colbert's inner ''Star Wars'' geek on ''The Late Show''|author=Dennis Perkins|date=2017-12-09|archivedate=20191121120959}}</ref>

He quoted ''Star Wars'' at least twice in his comic book roles: as Joker, he said ''"May the floss be with you"''; and as Trickster, he said "I am your father," as a role-reversal line from ''The Empire Strikes Back''.

Hamill played the villain "Cocknocker" in the [[2001]] [[Kevin Smith]] film [[Wikipedia:Jay and Silent Bob Strike Back|''Jay and Silent Bob Strike Back'']]. The film makes multiple references to ''Star Wars'', including a lightsaber-esque battle between Hamill's character and the title characters.<ref>[[Wikipedia:Jay and Silent Bob Strike Back|''Jay and Silent Bob Strike Back'']]</ref>

Hamill voiced co-star [[Harrison Ford]] (as [[Han Solo]]) in 2017 for the spoof video [[Wikipedia:Bad Lip Reading|''The Force Awakens: A Bad Lip Reading'']].<ref name="Lip">{{YouTube|video=Sv_hGITmNuo|text="THE FORCE AWAKENS: A Bad Lip Reading" (Featuring Mark Hamill as Han Solo)|channel=channel/UC67f2Qf7FYhtoUIF4Sf29cA|name=Bad Lip Reading|archivedate=20200708112402}}</ref>

